Some questioning the value of inflation swaps (driven mainly by crude prices) as a guide to coming Fed policy.  But, it is hard to ignore that the current repricing from cuts to hikes was concurrent with the surge in Oil prices.  So a retreat has to have some impact on the Fed's policy decisions but admittedly not exclusively as the labor market has strengthened in that timeframe as well.

@BlacklionCTA I could have made my arguments with just crude prices in this case.  But to your point, short term inflation swaps were very useful to me during the tariff surge, especially the 1-year 1-year forward swap

They do what they are supposed to do well.   Good indication of what headline inflation will be in the next year.  Of course, the biggest day to day driver is crude which may or may not be a concern to the Fed.   At times Fed may ignore crude prices for a variety of reasons and in those instances, swaps probably will not offer much insight

@davewmyers UST?

@davewmyers Warsh effect?

Fed and most observers were worried that lackluster job gains would feed on itself and cause a recession hence the insurance cuts of late last year.  Since then job gains have perked up and obviously no recession.   As far as real wages go, tariffs and crude prices are main culprits which were policy driven

Soothing Fed nerves. 1-year inflation swap down to 2.12 https://t.co/plYcpbepDX

@bharat16k July hike odds coming off slowly

@bharat16k No doubt, but hedging will dominate for now given DOTS

Because it generally is.  Fed tends look past one-time price adjustments like a surge in crude prices, but that goes out the window when you have too many of these surges as has been the case recently with COVID, Ukraine War, tariffs and then the Iran war.   That's one reason we moved from pricing cuts to pricing hikes.  Now that crude is retreating as reflected in the swap, Fed may has the option to wait this out.

@Donn1nger Not necessarily.  Crude prices have had a direct and indirect influence on many core categories like airline prices.

